<subSubSection id="A4BB4E844D25F863FF7C5ADECE5F5EDC" pageId="16" pageNumber="167" type="description">
<paragraph id="EC1E1D0F4D25F863FF7C5ADECE5F5EDC" blockId="16.[151,1437,1751,2030]" pageId="16" pageNumber="167">
<emphasis id="DED5C11D4D25F863FF7C5ADECB4A5FC0" bold="true" box="[199,345,1751,1777]" pageId="16" pageNumber="167">Description.</emphasis>
Forebody length 
<quantity id="2B59B0EA4D25F863FDA55AD1C86D5FC3" box="[542,638,1752,1778]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0699999999999998" pageId="16" pageNumber="167" unit="mm" value="10.7">10.7mm</quantity>
; HW/HL ratio = 1.2. Antennomere 3 subequal to 2; antennomere 4 subquadrate, without tomentose pubescence; antennomere 6 transverse. Mandibles more or less straight except apical tip. Eyes as long as 1/4 length of head; head appearing flat. Head and pronotum with small size punctures (see 
<figureCitation id="749A018A4D25F863FADE5B16CAF25E6F" captionStart="FIGURES 37–39" captionStartId="16.[151,264,1645,1669]" captionTargetBox="[291,1287,385,1614]" captionTargetId="figure-122@16.[281,1307,381,1621]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURES 37–39. Xanthopygus oliveirae Lynch. 37. Habitus photograph. 38. Pronotum. 39. Antenna. The pronotum of this specimen is depressed dorsally (probably due to preservation). Not to scale." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6048509" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6048509/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="167">Figs. 37–38</figureCitation>
); pronotum with one sparse row of punctures on each half beside median line; pronotum microsculpture with transverse lines. PW/PL ratio = 1.13. Mesoventrite with intercoxal process broad and rounded. Metacoxae with more than four spines (five or six) on posterior surface. EL/PL ratio = 1.41. Abdominal segments 4–6 without iridescent overtones; segment 6 without distinct bright band of orange coloration posteriorly; tergite 6 densely punctate; sternite 6 with two anterior transverse lines; segment 7 orange. No males are known.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="A4BB4E844D24F862FF7C5C9FCBB459C9" pageId="17" pageNumber="168" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="EC1E1D0F4D24F862FF7C5C9FC96A59E5" blockId="17.[151,1437,150,465]" pageId="17" pageNumber="168">
<emphasis id="DED5C11D4D24F862FF7C5C9FCB725981" bold="true" box="[199,353,150,176]" pageId="17" pageNumber="168">Distribution.</emphasis>
Known only from the original (lost) type and the 
<typeStatus id="331AA3AD4D24F862FC3E5C9EC9CD5980" box="[901,990,151,177]" pageId="17" pageNumber="168">neotype</typeStatus>
locality in 
<collectingCountry id="94B65D9F4D24F862FBEC5C9FCED95981" box="[1111,1226,150,176]" name="Argentina" pageId="17" pageNumber="168">Argentina</collectingCountry>
. The map is shown in 
<figureCitation id="749A018A4D24F862FF0F5CB3CB1059E5" box="[180,259,186,212]" captionStart="FIGURE 22" captionStartId="11.[151,250,1962,1986]" captionTargetBox="[195,1392,866,1938]" captionTargetId="figure-41@11.[195,1392,866,1938]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 22. Distribution map of X. luctuosus (Blanchard) (white squares), X. major (Bernhauer) (star), X. max Blackwelder (black squares) and X. oliveirae Lynch (circle)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6048497" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6048497/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="168">Fig. 22</figureCitation>
and online at https://www.simplemappr.net/map/16397.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="EC1E1D0F4D24F862FF7C5CD7CBB459C9" blockId="17.[151,1437,150,465]" box="[199,423,222,248]" pageId="17" pageNumber="168">
<emphasis id="DED5C11D4D24F862FF7C5CD7CB3959C9" bold="true" box="[199,298,222,248]" pageId="17" pageNumber="168">Habitat.</emphasis>
Unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="A4BB4E844D24F862FF7C5D0BCE7E58E0" pageId="17" pageNumber="168" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="EC1E1D0F4D24F862FF7C5D0BCE7E58E0" blockId="17.[151,1437,150,465]" pageId="17" pageNumber="168">
<emphasis id="DED5C11D4D24F862FF7C5D0BCB28582D" bold="true" box="[199,315,258,284]" pageId="17" pageNumber="168">Remarks.</emphasis>
The primary type is considered lost (Chani-Posse pers. comm.; the type was also not listed in any of the recent publications that discuss type materials from 
<collectingCountry id="94B65D9F4D24F862FCB65D2FC96F5871" box="[781,892,294,320]" name="Argentina" pageId="17" pageNumber="168">Argentina</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation id="883060FE4D24F862FC375D2FCE955871" author="Fernandez, L. A. &amp; Cabrera, N. &amp; Chani-Posse, M. &amp; Gabellone, C." box="[908,1158,294,320]" pageId="17" pageNumber="168" pagination="25 - 44" refId="ref20116" refString="Fernandez, L. A., Cabrera, N., Chani-Posse, M. &amp; Gabellone, C. (2007) Catalog of the types of Staphylinidae (Insecta, Coleoptera) deposited at Museo de La Plata (Argentina). Zootaxa, 1611 (1), 25 - 44. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 1611.1.2" type="journal article" year="2007">
Fernandez 
<emphasis id="DED5C11D4D24F862FBB15D2ECE575871" box="[1034,1092,294,320]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="168">et al.</emphasis>
2007
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="883060FE4D24F862FB285D2FCF835871" author="Bachmann, A. O. &amp; Chani-Posse, M. &amp; Guala, M. E. &amp; Newton, A. F." box="[1171,1424,294,320]" pageId="17" pageNumber="168" pagination="1 - 74" refId="ref19283" refString="Bachmann, A. O., Chani-Posse, M., Guala, M. E. &amp; Newton, A. F. (2017) A catalog of the types of Staphylinidae (Insecta, Coleoptera) deposited in the Museo Argentino de Ciencias Naturales, Buenos Aires (MACN). Zootaxa, 4223 (1), 1 - 74. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4223.1.1" type="journal article" year="2017">
Bachmann 
<emphasis id="DED5C11D4D24F862FAA85D2ECF5F5871" box="[1299,1356,294,320]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="168">et al.</emphasis>
2017
</bibRefCitation>
), and thus the designation of a 
<typeStatus id="331AA3AD4D24F862FE535D42C8525854" box="[488,577,331,357]" pageId="17" pageNumber="168">neotype</typeStatus>
is necessary. It is worth mentioning that the original type locality (given in the description) of Arrecifes [-34.06, -60.10] in 
<collectingCountry id="94B65D9F4D24F862FD145D67C90D58B9" box="[687,798,366,392]" name="Argentina" pageId="17" pageNumber="168">Argentina</collectingCountry>
has been transformed to agricultural fields and probably looks rather different now than just before 1884 when this species was described. The type locality (Arrecifes) is shown on the map, which is in close proximity to the 
<typeStatus id="331AA3AD4D24F862FD4B5DBEC95A58E0" box="[752,841,439,465]" pageId="17" pageNumber="168">neotype</typeStatus>
locality (‘Buenos Aires’).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
